# Versioning and changelog

Every push (top-level agent or Scenario A sub-agent) bumps [SemVer](https://semver.org) and appends a detailed entry to `CHANGELOG.md` ([Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com) format). Commits use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org). Applies in both `MODE: Cloud` and `MODE: Local`.

## Authoritative artifact

`CHANGELOG.md` at the repo root is canonical. Sync these too if present (any disagreement ŌåÆ fix the language field): `package.json#version`, `Cargo.toml#package.version`, `pyproject.toml#project.version` or `[tool.poetry].version`, `*.csproj#<Version>` or `<VersionPrefix>`, repo-root `VERSION` (single-line plaintext).

## Initialization (first time the repo lacks a CHANGELOG)

1. Infer **starting version** in priority order; first hit wins: (a) language metadata above; (b) repo-root `VERSION` if SemVer; (c) latest tag matching `^v?\d+\.\d+\.\d+$`; (d) SemVer-shaped string in pre-existing `CHANGELOG.md`; (e) fallback `0.0.0`.
2. First push bumps that starting version normally. If start was `0.0.0`, the first entry is `0.1.0` (signals "first tracked release").
3. Use `templates/CHANGELOG-initial.md` as the header template.
4. **Do not back-fill retroactive entries.** If the repo had a CHANGELOG in another format, leave old entries untouched below the new Keep a Changelog header.

## Version bump rules ŌĆö MUST

For each push, bump exactly one part of `MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`. Default = `PATCH`. Bump higher only with an explicit reason:

| Bump | When |
|------|------|
| `PATCH` (default) | Bug fixes, docs, internal refactors, test changes, CI changes, dependency bumps with no behavior change. |
| `MINOR` | New feature, new option, new env var, new public API surface ŌĆö all backward-compatible. |
| `MAJOR` | Removed/renamed public API, behavior changes that break existing users, product repositioning. |

When bumping `MINOR` or `MAJOR`, the `CHANGELOG.md` entry **must** include a `Bump reason: <one line>` directly under the version heading.

## Changelog entry ŌĆö MUST

Every push appends exactly one entry. Top of `CHANGELOG.md` is `[Unreleased]` (kept empty between releases) followed by the new dated entry above older ones.

Required structure for each entry (header + one-paragraph summary + applicable subsections):

```
## [X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD

<one-paragraph summary>

### Added | Changed | Fixed | Removed   (only sections that apply; omit empty ones)
### Breaking                              (MAJOR only ŌĆö list breaks + migration steps)
### Files / modules touched               (paths with one-phrase explanations)
### Verify                                (how the next agent or human confirms it works)
```

A handoff agent must be able to read the entry **without diff** and understand: what changed conceptually, why, what user-visible behavior changed, where to look in the code, and (if breaking) the migration. If you cannot fill `Files / modules touched` and `Verify` from your task plan, you do not yet understand your own change.

Banned entry content: `Updated some files`, `Various improvements`, `Refactor`, empty subsections, merging multiple pushes into one entry.

## Conventional Commits ŌĆö MUST

`<type>(<scope>): <subject>` on the first line, blank line, then `<body>`, then optional `<footer>`. Allowed types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `build`, `ci`, `perf`, `revert`. `<scope>` is an optional short noun (`rules`, `auth`, `ui`, ...). `<subject>` is imperative, Ōēż 72 chars, no trailing period. `<body>` explains what and why. Breaking changes: `BREAKING CHANGE: <description>` in the footer **and** bump `MAJOR`.

### Type ŌåÆ SemVer mapping

| Commit type | Default bump |
|-------------|--------------|
| `feat` | `MINOR` |
| `fix`, `perf` | `PATCH` |
| `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `build`, `ci` | `PATCH` |
| any commit with `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer | `MAJOR` |

Multi-commit push: bump matches the highest-impact commit.

## Language

Use the **project's primary user-facing documentation** language (see `00-universal-core.mdc` "Project documentation"); fallback = language of the user's most recent message. Don't mix within an entry. Conventional Commits keywords stay English.

## Tagging

Do not auto-tag every patch. Tagging is the user's call.

## Required report (in your final message)

- `Version: <old> ŌåÆ <new>` and the bump category (`PATCH | MINOR | MAJOR`).
- `CHANGELOG.md`: confirm the entry is present and dated today (UTC).
- `Synced version files: <list>` (`package.json`, `Cargo.toml`, ŌĆ”) or `none`.
